First, work can be alienating. Workers are often not in control of how they work, when they work, what is done with the goods and services they produce and what is done with the profits made from their work.

88
00:10:49,000 --> 00:11:02,000
Second, workers are not paid the full value of their labour, real wages have not kept pace with productivity driving economic inequality under decline in labour's share of income.

89
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:15,000
Third, people are time poor in the US. Full time employees work an average of 8.72 hours per day despite productivity increases.

90
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:24,000
Long working hours contribute to the feeling of time poverty, which has an adverse effect on psychological well-being.

91
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:45,000
Fourth, automation puts jobs and wages at risk. Technological innovation could in theory liberate people from the 40 hour work week, but unless changes are made to the structure of work, automation will simply exert downward pressure on wages and further diminish work opportunities.

92
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:54,000
So, what can be done to alleviate these problems? There are competing visions of the best way to arrive at a solution.

93
00:11:54,000 --> 00:12:06,000
One vision is what's known as the post-work position. The post-work theorists believe that work should not hold a central position in our lives or take up so much of our time.

94
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:22,000
They assert that although doing some work might be necessary, meaning, purpose and social value reside in the communities and relationships built and sustained outside of the workplace, thus life should be seen as an end in itself.

