00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:20,000
Recording 1, recent studies show that self-control and persistence increase academic outcomes independent of IQ. Even our personal beliefs about efforts can affect academic outcomes.

104
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:27,000
Children who think effort leads to achievement outperform those who believe ability is a fixed trait.

105
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:42,000
Given the link between persistence and academic success, decisions about effort are particularly important in childhood, yet relatively little research has explored how young children learn what's worth the effort.

106
00:14:43,000 --> 00:15:00,000
We all know that infants are keen observers of the social world, but they're not just idly watching, they are tiny learning machines, they can generalize such abstract concepts as causal relationships and social roles from just a few examples.

107
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:18,000
Even a 15-month-old infant can outperform a high-level computer in such tasks. Could infants also make broad, generalizable inferences from a few examples when it comes to effort? If so, there may be persistence isn't simply a character trait.

108
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:39,000
Maybe it's flexible and adaptable based on social context. To explore this question, we showed 15-month-old babies one of two things, an experimenter working hard to achieve two different goals or an experimenter who effortlessly reached each goal.

109
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:53,000
Then, we introduced the baby to a novel music toy that seemed as if it could be activated by pushing a big button on top. The button could be pressed down but didn't actually activate anything.

110
00:15:53,000 --> 00:16:00,000
Out of sight of the babies, we turned on the music toy with a hidden button so that they heard the toy making music.

111
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:17,000
We gave the babies the music toy and left the room. Then analysts who didn't know which condition each baby was in watched videotapes of the experiment and counted how many times babies try to activate the toy by pressing the button.

112
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:31,000
Across one study and a pre-registered duplication, babies who had seen an adult persist and succeed pushed the button about twice as many times as those who saw an adult effortlessly succeed.

113
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:41,000
In other words, babies learned that effort was valuable after watching just two examples of an adult working hard and succeeding.

114
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:53,000
Part of what's exciting about this finding is that the babies didn't just imitate the adult's actions, instead they generalised the value of effort to a novel task.

115
00:16:53,000 --> 00:17:07,000
The experimenter never demonstrated pushing a button or trying to make music. Instead, the babies learned from different examples of effortful actions that the new toy probably also required persistence.

