Question 23. Do you think Bostonians put out the welcome mat? Do you find other cities to be more or less polite?

140
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:06,000
Different cities have different fields for visitors. Some are friendly and open. Some are formal and distant.

141
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:13,000
Boston tends to seem hurried and sometimes a little rude. That's what some tourists have said.

142
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:22,000
One study found that people here are less willing to volunteer to help strangers than those residents of other US cities.

143
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:28,000
Take a closer look next time you're in Boston, and here are some of the things you'll probably see.

144
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:34,000
People smoking in the subway stations, despite the frequent reminders not to do so.

145
00:22:34,000 --> 00:22:40,000
Pedestrians walking when the crosswalk lights say not to do so, ignoring the cars.

146
00:22:40,000 --> 00:22:46,000
Car drivers speeding, making a loud noise with the horn, and occasionally, cursing at each other.

147
00:22:47,000 --> 00:22:55,000
Drives who can't be bothered to find a place to park, but instead simply turn on their blinker and stop in the middle of the street.

148
00:22:55,000 --> 00:23:02,000
Sometimes, Bostonians seem like they're just too busy to be polite. Why is there city like that?

149
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:13,000
Former US representative, Chester Atkins says it's because the Puritan founding fathers, with themselves impatient and bad tempered and had little time for courtesy.

150
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:17,000
That culture has carried down to the present day he believes.

151
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:29,000
Boston College professor Thomas O'Connor thinks a contributing factor is Boston's history as a city where each new group of immigrants was treated with suspicion and exclusion.

152
00:23:29,000 --> 00:23:34,000
That's given Boston a sense of clannishness and reserve he thinks.

153
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:41,000
The idea of a stranger greeting another stranger is simply not part of the local culture he says.

154
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:46,000
People would begin a conversation with someone they know, but not with a stranger.

155
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:57,000
Ralph Whitehead, a professor of journalism at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, thinks it's because Boston's upper class used manners to make class distinctions.

156
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:05,000
By being snobbish about manners, proper Bostonians made other people scornful of courtesy he says.

157
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:10,000
Some say that's just the way Boston is and that the city will never change.

158
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:16,000
Still, other cities with reputations for worse rudeness are trying hard to change their images.

159
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:27,000
Paris is one example where people are trying to be friendly. New York City is another. There, the city is trying to persuade subway riders to be more considerate.

160
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:32,000
If those cities can make the effort, maybe Boston should as well.

